---
// Serial — "The Nemo Disco 15" gear review.
// Third real article. Based on the user's own multi-week John Muir Trail
// field test of the bag (not a rewrite of any published review — content
// here is original, drawn from the user's firsthand trail notes). Images
// are official Nemo Equipment product-detail-page photography (sourced by
// the user directly from nemoequipment.com, not the earlier CleverHiker/
// Ian Krammer material that was deliberately left out — brand-owned
// product photography for a review of that exact product is standard
// editorial use, unlike reproducing a competing outlet's lifestyle shoot).
// Spec numbers in the LensSpec block (weight, fill power, comfort rating)
// are factual product data pulled from Nemo's own product page.
import SerialLayout from "../../layouts/SerialLayout.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/serial/Nav.astro";
import Hero from "../../components/serial/Hero.astro";
import ImageGrid from "../../components/serial/ImageGrid.astro";
import ArticleSection from "../../components/serial/ArticleSection.astro";
import PullQuote from "../../components/serial/PullQuote.astro";
import LensSpec from "../../components/serial/LensSpec.astro";
import RatingStrip from "../../components/serial/RatingStrip.astro";
import RelatedGrid from "../../components/serial/RelatedGrid.astro";
import Paywall from "../../components/serial/Paywall.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/serial/Footer.astro";
---

<SerialLayout
	title="The Nemo Disco 15 — Cocoon Mode on the JMT — Serial"
	description="A field review of the Nemo Disco 15 sleeping bag after two and a half weeks on the John Muir Trail."
>
	<Nav />

	<Hero
		kicker="Gear / Backpacking"
		category="Review"
		title="The Nemo Disco 15 — Cocoon Mode on the JMT"
		image={{ src: "/images/serial/hero-nemo-disco-15.jpg", alt: "A camper unfurling a navy and gold Nemo Disco 15 sleeping bag beside a tent at a lakeside campsite" }}
	/>

	<div class="wrap">
		<div class="section" style="padding-top:56px">
			<p class="lede">
				<span class="drop">A multi-week trail is a long stress test for a sleep system</span> — full
				sun down to below-freezing nights, no do-overs if something in the kit doesn't hold up. The
				Nemo Disco 15 rode along for two and a half weeks on the John Muir Trail, through the whole
				range of conditions the JMT throws at you, and came out the other side as one of the few
				pieces of gear with zero complaints.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="2"
		tiles={[
			{
				tag: "Disco 15",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/nemo-disco-15-profile.jpg", alt: "Side profile of the Nemo Disco 15 sleeping bag, closed, navy with gold zipper accents" },
			},
			{
				tag: "Blanket Fold",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/nemo-disco-15-flatlay.jpg", alt: "Top-down view of the Nemo Disco 15 with the hood and gold Blanket Fold collar open" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="01" title="A Wide Temperature Window">
		<p>
			The range is the headline. This bag adapted well across everything the JMT threw at it, down to
			below freezing at altitude, without ever feeling like the wrong bag for the night. That's mostly
			down to the Thermo Gills — the two chest vents, each with its own inner and outer zipper. On
			colder nights they stay sealed and the bag runs warm; the second temperatures climb, cracking
			the gills open dumps just enough heat without fully unzipping and losing the warmth you've
			already built up. That flexibility, more than the quoted comfort rating, is what made one bag
			work for the whole trip.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="wide"
		tiles={[
			{
				aspect: "16 / 6",
				tag: "Thermo Gill",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/nemo-disco-15-thermogill.jpg", alt: "Three-quarter angle of the Nemo Disco 15 showing the Thermo Gill vent zippers along the torso" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<PullQuote
		quote="Close the collar and it doesn't ease you into warm. It's immediate — a heated cocoon the second it seals."
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="02" title="Small Footprint, Long Trail">
		<p>
			On a trip measured in weeks instead of nights, packed size matters as much as anything the bag
			does once you're in it. The Disco compresses down small enough that it never read as the
			sacrifice a roomier bag usually is — which matters more the longer the trail gets, since every
			cubic inch it doesn't take up is one more you get back for food or layers.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="wide"
		tiles={[
			{
				aspect: "16 / 6",
				tag: "Packed Size",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/nemo-disco-15-packed.jpg", alt: "The Nemo Disco 15 compressed in its stuff sack next to a standard Nalgene bottle for scale" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<LensSpec
		name="Nemo Disco 15"
		sn="Endless Promise Collection &middot; 650 FP RDS down"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Comfort", v: "15&deg;F / 30&deg;F options" },
			{ k: "Weight", v: "2 lb 11 oz" },
			{ k: "Fill", v: "650 FP" },
		]}
		verdict="JMT-approved"
	>
		Spec sheet numbers are Nemo's own, not a substitute for the trail test above — but they explain
		why the bag performs the way it does. The 650-fill down and dual Thermo Gills are doing the actual
		work described in the temperature-range section.
	</LensSpec>

	<RatingStrip
		ratings={[
			{ label: "Warmth", value: "Wide range" },
			{ label: "Packed size", value: "Compact" },
			{ label: "Comfort", value: "Excellent" },
			{ label: "Verdict", value: "Keeper" },
		]}
	/>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="wide"
		tiles={[
			{
				aspect: "16 / 6",
				tag: "Collar Open",
				image: { src: "/images/serial/nemo-disco-15-collar-open.jpg", alt: "Angled view of the Nemo Disco 15 with the gold Blanket Fold collar and hood open" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="03" title="The Cocoon">
		<p>
			The closure flap is the detail that sells the bag. Pull it into place and it doesn't ease you
			into warm — it's immediate, sealing off the collar and turning the whole bag into a heated
			cocoon the second it closes. The hood does its own version of the same trick: it's plush enough
			on its own that a pillow stopped being necessary, one less thing to carry or improvise with a
			stuffed jacket.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ArticleSection number="04" title="Sizing: Long vs. Regular">
		<p>
			One genuine caveat, and it's about fit rather than performance. At 6 feet, the Long size ran
			slightly large — some of that is probably the spoon shape itself rather than the length, coming
			from a mummy-bag background where the bag moves with you rather than the other way around. The
			extra room isn't wasted: you can turn over inside the bag instead of turning the whole bag with
			you, which is a real comfort upgrade on a multi-week trip. The trade-off is that more internal
			volume takes longer to heat up. If low-temperature performance is the priority over roominess,
			it's worth sizing down to Regular even right at the height cutoff.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

